Dependencies
============

Install rabbitmq on a server:
 echo deb http://www.rabbitmq.com/debian/ testing main > /etc/apt/sources.list.d/rabbitmq.list
 apt-get update
 apt-get install rabbitmq-server

On that server, for the demos we'll need:
 rabbitmqctl add_vhost ruote-test
 rabbitmqctl add_user ruote ruote
 rabbitmqctl set_permissions -p ruote-test ruote '.*' '.*' '.*'

Ruby
====
Ruby package management on Debian is.... interesting. It doesn't
integrate naturally with native packaging. TBD.

apt-get install build-essential git-core ruby1.9.1-full rubygems1.9.1

On Debian ruby1.9 may not be fully configured (CHECK). This may be
useful (see http://krnjevic.com/wp/?p=209 )

update-alternatives --install /usr/bin/ruby ruby /usr/bin/ruby1.9.1 400 \
--slave   /usr/share/man/man1/ruby.1.gz ruby.1.gz \
/usr/share/man/man1/ruby1.9.1.1.gz \
--slave   /usr/bin/ri ri /usr/bin/ri1.9.1 \
--slave   /usr/bin/irb irb /usr/bin/irb1.9.1 \
--slave   /usr/bin/gem gem /usr/bin/gem1.9.1 \

update-alternatives --config gem

We need Bundler so as root:
  gem1.8 install bundler
and/or
  gem1.9.1 install bundler

Ruote + Co
==========

To install dependent gems, pull the git sources and install them run:
  ./setup.sh

(Note that rpsec seems to need to be installed as a gem)


Demo
====

See the demo/README info
Run ./RUN_DEMO.sh



Python
======

Dependencies:
  python-amqplib


Managing Modules/Gems in Deployment
===================================

Two options : RVM and Bundler

RVM appears to be a little like buildout for python
rvm's primary use case is making it easy to install + test out multiple ruby interpeters fwiw
  http://rvm.beginrescueend.com

rvm is used by the ruoute team.

To install:
 # echo 'rvm_path=/maemo/devel/rvm/' > $HOME/.rvmrc
 bash < <( curl http://rvm.beginrescueend.com/releases/rvm-install-head )

Then follow instructions to install (or optionally use
 source $HOME/.rvm/scripts/rvm
or
 source $rvm_path/scripts/rvm
in each ruby shell

RVM is a bit like gentoo - it builds *everything* (including ruby itself)

Bundler is about avoiding vendor gems and keeps gems installed locally
to the project. It's probably a sufficient solution and may be cleaner
too.

http://gembundler.com/